SENATE JOINT RESOLUTION 937
By Stevens
A RESOLUTION to honor and congratulate Tabitha Bates on her
selection as a 2026 Extraordinary Educator.
WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly should pause to
specially recognize those outstanding teachers who have devoted their careers to providing the
highest-quality education for Tennessee's students; and
WHEREAS, Tabitha Bates of Dover is one such estimable educator, who has
distinguished herself as a professional of the greatest dedication, ability, and integrity; and
WHEREAS, Mrs. Bates has been selected as a 2026 Extraordinary Educator by
Curriculum Associates, a most befitting honor that recognizes the positive influence she has on
so many young lives; and
WHEREAS, the Curriculum Associates Extraordinary Educators program is an annual
tradition of celebrating and connecting best-in-class educators who demonstrate established
criteria; Extraordinary Educators receive local and national recognition, a network of peers from
around the country, professional learning opportunities, and the opportunity to attend the
Extraordinary Educators Leadership Summit; and
WHEREAS, a fifth-grade math teacher at Dover Elementary School, Tabitha Bates is an
extremely talented and compassionate educator who works assiduously to motivate her
students to reach their full potential, both as scholars and as citizens; and
WHEREAS, she earned her undergraduate degree from Murray State University and is
currently pursuing a degree in educational leadership at Austin Peay State University; and
WHEREAS, during her twenty-three years as an educator, Mrs. Bates has taught
mathematics and English language arts; she began her career at Erin Elementary School in
Houston County and came on board at Dover Elementary two decades ago; and
SJR0937
015521
- 1 -

WHEREAS, known for her unique approach to teaching both in and out of the
classroom, Tabitha Bates firmly believes that all students can learn, no matter their background;
she strives to continuously improve her instruction and enhance student learning while making
meaningful connections with her students; and
WHEREAS, leveraging i-Ready data to guide instruction, identify areas for intervention
and enrichment, and support meaningful goal setting with her students, Mrs. Bates has seen
significant gains among her students in the past two years on the i-Ready Diagnostic and the
TCAP state assessment, with some reaching grade-level proficiency after years of struggle; and
WHEREAS, Tabitha Bates is the founder of Panther Pantry, a program she launched
four years ago to support students and families in need by providing food, hygiene products,
and other essential resources; she created the pantry in remembrance of her father, and today,
she runs the pantry with the help of a dedicated team of students, the guidance counselor, and
a fellow teacher, making it a school-wide effort in compassion and service; and
WHEREAS, Mrs. Bates enjoys the love and support of her husband of twenty-four years,
Casey Bates, and her son, Montana Bates; she is active in her church and guided by her faith in
all she does; and
WHEREAS, Tabitha Bates is an inspiration to her colleagues and students alike, and her
friendship and counsel are highly valued by those who are fortunate to know her; and
WHEREAS, Mrs. Bates truly epitomizes the dedicated teacher who is wholly committed
to the highest ideals of public service and quality education for all, and she should be specially
recognized; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE ONE HUNDRED FOURTEENTH
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE HOUSE OF
REPRESENTATIVES CONCURRING, that we hereby honor and congratulate Tabitha Bates on
her selection as a 2026 Extraordinary Educator, commend her exceptional service to the
- 2 - 015521

children of Tennessee, salute her professional expertise and personal excellence, and wish her
all the best in her future endeavors.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
